    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d1cc697f_78239eed",
        "filename": "android/base/system/Process_posix.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 77,
      "author": {
        "id": 1087048
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-03-28T19:40:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Since start() is non-blocking doesn\u0027t this mean that we won\u0027t get the signal if the process terminates after the second pthread_sigmask if SIGCHLD was blocked before this?\n\nIn general I\u0027m not a fan of relying on signals here since it creates a very non-obvious dependency between different parts of the program and as we have seen the sigmask can change any time and we won\u0027t be able to catch all the problems that might happen because of it.\n\nI realize this is probably not the unix way but I think having a separate ProcessReaper class (or some other name) running in its own thread that\u0027s responsible for reaping processes would be a better idea. That way it becomes much more clear where reaping happens and who is responsible. With such a design we could have callbacks on process exits similar to what QProcess has and we never have to worry about sigmasks.\n\nThe same design could be used for Windows although I think in that case we might not need to have the Reaper run its own thread, it could use callback based waits to use an OS worker thread instead which I think is more efficient. But the interface and outward behavior would be the same for all OS\u0027s.\n\nThis would also require some changes to how we wait for processes, but this could be done with a condition variable instead in that case.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 72,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 77,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "881470755f6fefbba997b0f383501ce58e94738f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
